  "conclusions": [
    "Teacher solves the symmetric left/right default-intro cases reliably (mean success 0.887), while the v3 policy fails them (mean success 0.000, mean timeout 0.675, mean max lateral excursion 0.972).",
    "The encoder is not obstacle-blind: sweeping one obstacle changes the deterministic action by up to 35.38 degrees (median 6.64 degrees).",
    "Reset sampling is roughly symmetric, so the failure is not explained by a left/right data imbalance (left=22, right=26, imbalance=0.083).",
    "The saved v3 run never reached target_default_intro; it stalled earlier at target_bypass_commit_v2.",
    "At the fallback stage, success collapsed while safety margin improved: best success 0.417, latest success 0.0, early mean lateral error 0.652, late mean lateral error 1.955, early mean clearance 0.269, late mean clearance 0.364.",
    "That pattern matches over-avoidance and failed rejoin: the policy becomes safer around obstacles but drifts far off-route and times out instead of committing back to goal.",
    "The next curriculum should therefore keep v4's visibility/symmetry fixes, but add stronger anti-drift pressure around target_bypass_commit_v2 through target_default: reduce reward for wide bypassing once safe, increase rejoin/remaining-distance pressure, and tighten recovery/teacher support on the stage where collapse starts."
